### Understanding Linked Lists

A linked list is a sequence of nodes where each node contains data and a pointer to the next node. Unlike arrays, linked lists don't need contiguous memory — each node can be anywhere in the heap.

**Why linked lists appear in interviews:**
- They test pointer manipulation skills
- Many problems require in-place modification
- They're the foundation for more complex structures (trees, graphs)

**Key techniques:**
- **Dummy head node**: simplifies edge cases (empty list, single node)
- **Two pointers (fast/slow)**: detect cycles, find middle, find nth from end
- **Reversal**: iterative (3 pointers) or recursive
- **Merge**: combine two sorted lists

**Common mistakes:**
- Forgetting to handle null/empty list
- Losing reference to the head after modification
- Not handling single-node lists
- Infinite loops when cycle exists

## Doubly Linked List & LRU Cache Implementation

```mermaid
graph TD
    App[Application] --> Cache{Cache Hit?}
    Cache -->|Hit| Return[Return Data]
    Cache -->|Miss| DB[(Database)]
    DB --> Update[Update Cache]
    Update --> Return
```


A doubly linked list adds a `prev` pointer to each node, enabling O(1) removal of any node when you have a direct reference to it (no need to traverse from the head). This property, combined with a hash map, is the foundation of the LRU (Least Recently Used) Cache — one of the most popular system design coding questions.

The LRU Cache requires two operations in O(1): `get(key)` and `put(key, value)`. The hash map provides O(1) key lookup. The doubly linked list maintains access order — most recently used at the head (or tail, by convention), least recently used at the other end. On every access, move the node to the most-recently-used position. On capacity overflow, remove the least-recently-used node (from the other end).

Using sentinel (dummy) head and tail nodes simplifies boundary conditions — you never need to check for null neighbors when inserting or removing. This reduces bugs significantly.

### Python Example
```python
class DLinkedNode:
    def __init__(self, key=0, val=0):
        self.key = key
        self.val = val
        self.prev = self.next = None

class LRUCache:
    def __init__(self, capacity: int):
        self.cap = capacity
        self.cache = {}  # key -> node
        # Dummy sentinels: head <-> ... <-> tail
        self.head = DLinkedNode()
        self.tail = DLinkedNode()
        self.head.next = self.tail
        self.tail.prev = self.head

    def _remove(self, node):
        node.prev.next = node.next
        node.next.prev = node.prev

    def _insert_front(self, node):
        node.next = self.head.next
        node.prev = self.head
        self.head.next.prev = node
        self.head.next = node

    def get(self, key: int) -> int:
        if key not in self.cache:
            return -1
        node = self.cache[key]
        self._remove(node)
        self._insert_front(node)
        return node.val

    def put(self, key: int, value: int) -> None:
        if key in self.cache:
            self._remove(self.cache[key])
        node = DLinkedNode(key, value)
        self.cache[key] = node
        self._insert_front(node)
        if len(self.cache) > self.cap:
            lru = self.tail.prev
            self._remove(lru)
            del self.cache[lru.key]
```

### Java Example
```java
class LRUCache {
    private Map<Integer, Node> cache = new HashMap<>();
    private int cap;
    private Node head = new Node(0, 0), tail = new Node(0, 0);

    public LRUCache(int capacity) {
        this.cap = capacity;
        head.next = tail; tail.prev = head;
    }
    private void remove(Node n) {
        n.prev.next = n.next; n.next.prev = n.prev;
    }
    private void insertFront(Node n) {
        n.next = head.next; n.prev = head;
        head.next.prev = n; head.next = n;
    }
    public int get(int key) {
        if (!cache.containsKey(key)) return -1;
        Node n = cache.get(key); remove(n); insertFront(n);
        return n.val;
    }
    public void put(int key, int value) {
        if (cache.containsKey(key)) remove(cache.get(key));
        Node n = new Node(key, value);
        cache.put(key, n); insertFront(n);
        if (cache.size() > cap) {
            Node lru = tail.prev;
            remove(lru); cache.remove(lru.key);
        }
    }
}
```

### Complexity Analysis
- **get**: O(1) — hash map lookup + O(1) doubly linked list move
- **put**: O(1) — hash map insert + O(1) doubly linked list insert/remove
- **Space**: O(capacity) for both map and list
- Python's `OrderedDict` can implement LRU in fewer lines but interviewers want you to implement from scratch

### Common Interview Questions
- LeetCode 146 — LRU Cache
- LeetCode 460 — LFU Cache (harder variant)
- LeetCode 432 — All O(1) Data Structure

**Interview Tip:** LRU Cache is asked in both coding and system design rounds. In coding, implement from scratch — don't use OrderedDict. In system design, discuss eviction policies: LRU, LFU, FIFO, and their trade-offs. The interviewer wants to see you connect the data structure to the real-world caching problem.

## Flattening Multilevel Lists & Skip Lists Concepts

```mermaid
graph LR
    H[Head] --> A[1] --> B[2] --> C[3] --> D[4] --> N[null]
```


A multilevel doubly linked list has nodes that may have a `child` pointer to another doubly linked list. Flattening means merging all levels into a single-level doubly linked list where all nodes appear in depth-first order. This is essentially DFS on a linked structure.

The iterative approach: when you encounter a node with a child, (1) find the tail of the child list, (2) connect the tail to `node.next`, (3) connect `node.next` to `child`, (4) set `child` to null, then continue iterating. This in-place approach runs in O(n) time and O(1) space (excluding the recursion stack of a recursive version).

A **skip list** is an advanced probabilistic data structure built on top of a sorted linked list, with multiple "express lane" layers for O(log n) average search, insert, and delete. While rarely implemented in interviews, it's a common system design topic — Redis uses skip lists for its sorted sets because they support efficient range queries and are simpler to implement than balanced BSTs.

### Python Example
```python
class Node:
    def __init__(self, val, prev=None, next=None, child=None):
        self.val = val
        self.prev = prev
        self.next = next
        self.child = child

def flatten(head: Node) -> Node:
    if not head:
        return None
    curr = head
    while curr:
        if curr.child:
            child = curr.child
            next_node = curr.next
            # Find tail of child list
            tail = child
            while tail.next:
                tail = tail.next
            # Connect curr -> child
            curr.next = child
            child.prev = curr
            curr.child = None
            # Connect tail -> next_node
            tail.next = next_node
            if next_node:
                next_node.prev = tail
        curr = curr.next
    return head

def flatten_recursive(head: Node) -> Node:
    if not head:
        return None
    if head.child:
        child_tail = flatten_recursive(head.child)
        child_head = head.child
        rest = head.next
        head.next = child_head
        child_head.prev = head
        head.child = None
        child_tail.next = rest
        if rest:
            rest.prev = child_tail
    if head.next:
        flatten_recursive(head.next)
    return head

# Skip List search (conceptual)
class SkipList:
    def search(self, target: int) -> bool:
        curr = self.head  # Start at top-left sentinel
        for level in reversed(range(self.max_level)):
            while curr.next[level] and curr.next[level].val < target:
                curr = curr.next[level]  # Move right
        curr = curr.next[0]  # Drop to bottom level
        return curr is not None and curr.val == target
```

### Java Example
```java
public Node flatten(Node head) {
    Node curr = head;
    while (curr != null) {
        if (curr.child != null) {
            Node child = curr.child;
            Node next = curr.next;
            Node tail = child;
            while (tail.next != null) tail = tail.next;
            curr.next = child; child.prev = curr; curr.child = null;
            tail.next = next; if (next != null) next.prev = tail;
        }
        curr = curr.next;
    }
    return head;
}
```

### Complexity Analysis
- **Flatten (iterative)**: O(n) time, O(1) space where n = total nodes across all levels
- **Flatten (recursive)**: O(n) time, O(d) space where d = depth of nesting
- **Skip list search**: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case
- **Skip list insert/delete**: O(log n) average

### Common Interview Questions
- LeetCode 430 — Flatten a Multilevel Doubly Linked List
- LeetCode 1206 — Design Skiplist
- LeetCode 716 — Max Stack (uses doubly linked list + map)

**Interview Tip:** The flatten problem tests your ability to manipulate multiple pointer connections simultaneously. Write out the four pointer assignments before coding: `curr.next = child`, `child.prev = curr`, `tail.next = next`, `next.prev = tail`. Doing this systematically prevents missing a pointer.

## Mock Interview & Linked List Pattern Consolidation

```mermaid
graph LR
    H[Head] --> A[1] --> B[2] --> C[3] --> D[4] --> N[null]
```


Linked list problems are a staple of technical interviews at all levels. The patterns are fewer than arrays but require precise pointer reasoning. This session consolidates everything into a decision framework and shows how to recognize which technique applies within the first minute of reading a problem.

**Linked List Pattern Recognition Guide:**
1. "Detect/find cycle" → Fast/slow pointers (Floyd's)
2. "Find middle" → Fast/slow pointers
3. "Reverse" → Three-pointer iterative (prev, curr, next)
4. "Remove nth from end" → Two pointers with N-gap
5. "Merge sorted lists" → Dummy head + comparison loop
6. "Intersection of two lists" → Redirect pointers trick
7. "O(1) get/put cache" → Hash map + doubly linked list
8. "Sort linked list" → Merge sort (find mid + merge)

### Python: Core Templates
```python
# Template 1: Fast/Slow for cycle and middle
def fast_slow_template(head):
    slow = fast = head
    while fast and fast.next:
        slow = slow.next
        fast = fast.next.next
        if slow is fast:  # cycle detected
            return slow
    return slow  # middle of list if no cycle

# Template 2: Three-pointer reversal
def reverse_template(head):
    prev, curr = None, head
    while curr:
        nxt = curr.next
        curr.next = prev
        prev, curr = curr, nxt
    return prev  # new head

# Template 3: Dummy head for building lists
def build_list_template(*lists):
    dummy = curr = ListNode(0)
    # ... append nodes to curr.next, advance curr ...
    return dummy.next

# Template 4: Two-pointer with gap
def nth_from_end_template(head, n):
    dummy = ListNode(0)
    dummy.next = head
    fast = slow = dummy
    for _ in range(n + 1):
        fast = fast.next
    while fast:
        fast = fast.next
        slow = slow.next
    slow.next = slow.next.next
    return dummy.next
```

### Java: Interview Checklist
```java
// Before coding any linked list problem, ask yourself:
// 1. Do I need a dummy head? (building new list, removing head possible)
// 2. Single or double pass? (nth from end = single pass with gap)
// 3. Do I modify the original list? (clarify with interviewer)
// 4. Any cycle? (avoid infinite loops in traversal)
// 5. Edge cases: empty list, single node, two nodes

public boolean isPalindrome(ListNode head) {
    ListNode slow = head, fast = head;
    while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
        slow = slow.next;
        fast = fast.next.next;
    }
    // Reverse second half
    ListNode prev = null, curr = slow;
    while (curr != null) {
        ListNode tmp = curr.next; curr.next = prev; prev = curr; curr = tmp;
    }
    // Compare
    ListNode left = head, right = prev;
    while (right != null) {
        if (left.val != right.val) return false;
        left = left.next; right = right.next;
    }
    return true;
}
```

### Complexity Quick Reference
| Pattern | Time | Space |
|---------|------|-------|
| Reverse | O(n) | O(1) |
| Cycle Detection | O(n) | O(1) |
| Merge Two Sorted | O(m+n) | O(1) |
| Merge K Sorted | O(N log K) | O(K) |
| LRU Cache ops | O(1) | O(cap) |
| Sort List | O(n log n) | O(log n) |

