## Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters

```mermaid
graph LR
    Key[Key] --> Hash[Hash Function]
    Hash --> B0[Bucket 0]
    Hash --> B1[Bucket 1]
    Hash --> B2[Bucket 2]
    B1 --> N1[Node A] --> N2[Node B]
```


Find the length of the longest substring of a string that contains no repeated characters. This is the canonical sliding window + hash map problem.

**Sliding window approach:** Maintain a window `[left, right]`. Expand `right` one character at a time. Track the last seen index of each character in a hash map. If `s[right]` was seen at or after `left`, jump `left` to `last_seen[s[right]] + 1` to exclude the duplicate. Update `last_seen` and track the max window size.

```python
def length_of_longest_substring(s: str) -> int:
    last_seen = {}   # char -> last index seen
    left = 0
    max_len = 0

    for right, ch in enumerate(s):
        if ch in last_seen and last_seen[ch] >= left:
            left = last_seen[ch] + 1  # shrink window
        last_seen[ch] = right
        max_len = max(max_len, right - left + 1)

    return max_len


# Return the actual substring too
def longest_substring_no_repeat(s: str) -> str:
    last_seen = {}
    left = 0
    best_start, best_len = 0, 0

    for right, ch in enumerate(s):
        if ch in last_seen and last_seen[ch] >= left:
            left = last_seen[ch] + 1
        last_seen[ch] = right
        if right - left + 1 > best_len:
            best_len = right - left + 1
            best_start = left

    return s[best_start: best_start + best_len]


# Tests
assert length_of_longest_substring("abcabcbb") == 3  # "abc"
assert length_of_longest_substring("bbbbb")    == 1  # "b"
assert length_of_longest_substring("pwwkew")   == 3  # "wke"
assert length_of_longest_substring("")         == 0
```

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class LongestSubstring {
    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        Map<Character, Integer> lastSeen = new HashMap<>();
        int left = 0, maxLen = 0;

        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {
            char ch = s.charAt(right);
            if (lastSeen.containsKey(ch) && lastSeen.get(ch) >= left) {
                left = lastSeen.get(ch) + 1;
            }
            lastSeen.put(ch, right);
            maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
        }
        return maxLen;
    }
}
```

**Complexity**
- Time: O(n) — each character is visited at most twice (right advances n times, left never goes back)
- Space: O(min(n, |alphabet|)) — hash map bounded by charset size

**Interview Tip:** This pattern — sliding window with a hash map tracking last occurrence — extends to: Longest Substring with At Most K Distinct Characters (use frequency map, shrink when distinct count exceeds K), and Minimum Window Substring (LC 76). Always state the window invariant: 'left to right contains no duplicate characters'.

