## 0/1 Knapsack

```mermaid
graph TD
    F5[fib 5] --> F4[fib 4]
    F5 --> F3a[fib 3]
    F4 --> F3b[fib 3]
    F4 --> F2a[fib 2]
    F3a --> F2b[fib 2]
    F3a --> F1a[fib 1]
```


The 0/1 Knapsack problem: given n items each with a weight and value, and a knapsack with capacity W, find the maximum value achievable without exceeding the capacity. Each item can be taken at most once (0 or 1 times). This is the archetype of DP problems involving binary choices and capacity constraints.

The DP state is dp[i][w] = maximum value using the first i items with capacity w. Recurrence: if item i is skipped, dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]; if item i is taken (only if weight[i] <= w), dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w - weight[i]] + value[i]. Take the maximum. Base case: dp[0][w] = 0 for all w.

Space optimization: since dp[i] only depends on dp[i-1], we can use a 1D array and iterate weights from right to left (to avoid using an item twice). Iterating left to right in the 1D array would mean item i could be used multiple times — which is the Unbounded Knapsack variant. The iteration direction is the key distinction.

```python
# 2D DP - easier to understand
def knapsack_2d(weights, values, W):
    n = len(weights)
    dp = [[0] * (W + 1) for _ in range(n + 1)]
    for i in range(1, n + 1):
        for w in range(W + 1):
            dp[i][w] = dp[i-1][w]  # skip item i
            if weights[i-1] <= w:
                dp[i][w] = max(dp[i][w],
                               dp[i-1][w - weights[i-1]] + values[i-1])
    return dp[n][W]

# 1D DP - space optimized (iterate right to left!)
def knapsack_1d(weights, values, W):
    dp = [0] * (W + 1)
    for i in range(len(weights)):
        for w in range(W, weights[i] - 1, -1):  # RIGHT TO LEFT
            dp[w] = max(dp[w], dp[w - weights[i]] + values[i])
    return dp[W]

# Unbounded Knapsack (each item can be used multiple times)
def knapsack_unbounded(weights, values, W):
    dp = [0] * (W + 1)
    for w in range(W + 1):
        for i in range(len(weights)):
            if weights[i] <= w:
                dp[w] = max(dp[w], dp[w - weights[i]] + values[i])  # LEFT TO RIGHT
    return dp[W]
```

```java
public class Knapsack {
    public int knapsack01(int[] weights, int[] values, int W) {
        int n = weights.length;
        int[] dp = new int[W + 1];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            // Iterate RIGHT to LEFT for 0/1 knapsack
            for (int w = W; w >= weights[i]; w--) {
                dp[w] = Math.max(dp[w], dp[w - weights[i]] + values[i]);
            }
        }
        return dp[W];
    }

    public int knapsackUnbounded(int[] weights, int[] values, int W) {
        int[] dp = new int[W + 1];
        for (int w = 0; w <= W; w++) {
            for (int i = 0; i < weights.length; i++) {
                if (weights[i] <= w)
                    dp[w] = Math.max(dp[w], dp[w - weights[i]] + values[i]);
            }
        }
        return dp[W];
    }
}
```

**Complexity:** Time O(n × W), Space O(W) with 1D optimization.

**Interview Tip:** The direction of inner loop iteration is the most common mistake and interview gotcha. Right-to-left = each item used at most once (0/1). Left-to-right = each item can be reused (unbounded). Explain this trade-off explicitly — it shows deep understanding of DP state transitions.

