## Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)

The Longest Common Subsequence (LCS) of two strings is the longest sequence of characters that appears in both strings in the same relative order, but not necessarily contiguously. LCS is foundational to diff tools, bioinformatics sequence alignment, and plagiarism detection. It is the base problem for a family of string DP problems.

DP state: dp[i][j] = length of LCS of s1[:i] and s2[:j]. Recurrence: if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1], dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1 (extend the match). Otherwise, dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) (skip one character from either string). Base case: dp[0][j] = dp[i][0] = 0.

Space optimization to O(min(m, n)) is possible since each row only needs the previous row. Rolling array reduces from O(mn) to O(n). LCS can be extended to reconstruct the actual subsequence by backtracking through the DP table. Related problems: Edit Distance, Shortest Common Supersequence, and Longest Palindromic Subsequence all build on LCS.

```python
def lcs(s1, s2):
    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])
    return dp[m][n]

def lcs_reconstruct(s1, s2):
    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1
            else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])
    # Backtrack to find the actual LCS
    i, j = m, n
    result = []
    while i > 0 and j > 0:
        if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
            result.append(s1[i-1])
            i -= 1; j -= 1
        elif dp[i-1][j] > dp[i][j-1]:
            i -= 1
        else:
            j -= 1
    return ''.join(reversed(result))

# Longest Palindromic Subsequence = LCS(s, reverse(s))
def longest_palindromic_subseq(s):
    return lcs(s, s[::-1])
```

```java
public class LCS {
    public int longestCommonSubsequence(String s1, String s2) {
        int m = s1.length(), n = s2.length();
        int[][] dp = new int[m + 1][n + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i-1) == s2.charAt(j-1))
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1;
                else
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]);
            }
        }
        return dp[m][n];
    }

    // Space optimized O(n)
    public int lcsOptimized(String s1, String s2) {
        int m = s1.length(), n = s2.length();
        int[] prev = new int[n + 1], curr = new int[n + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i-1) == s2.charAt(j-1))
                    curr[j] = prev[j-1] + 1;
                else
                    curr[j] = Math.max(prev[j], curr[j-1]);
            }
            int[] tmp = prev; prev = curr; curr = tmp;
            Arrays.fill(curr, 0);
        }
        return prev[n];
    }
}
```

**Complexity:** Time O(m × n), Space O(m × n) full table, O(n) with rolling array.

**Interview Tip:** Longest Palindromic Subsequence, Shortest Common Supersequence, and Minimum Insertions to Make a String Palindrome all reduce to LCS. When stuck on a string DP problem, try framing it as LCS with a transformed input — this reuse is a powerful problem-solving meta-skill.

