```java
// Java — permutations without duplicates
import java.util.*;

public class Permutations {
    public List<List<Integer>> permute(int[] nums) {
        List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        backtrack(nums, new boolean[nums.length], new ArrayList<>(), result);
        return result;
    }

    private void backtrack(int[] nums, boolean[] used,
                           List<Integer> path, List<List<Integer>> result) {
        if (path.size() == nums.length) {
            result.add(new ArrayList<>(path));
            return;
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            if (used[i]) continue;
            used[i] = true;
            path.add(nums[i]);
            backtrack(nums, used, path, result);
            path.remove(path.size() - 1);
            used[i] = false;
        }
    }
}
```

**Complexity:**
- Without duplicates: O(n! * n) time (n! permutations, each of length n), O(n) auxiliary stack space.
- With duplicates: still O(n! * n) worst case but pruning reduces actual work significantly.

**Interview Tip:** The duplicate-skipping condition `nums[i] == nums[i-1] && !used[i-1]` is the key insight interviewers test. It ensures that among duplicate values, we always use the leftmost occurrence first, giving a canonical ordering.

