Fill a 9×9 grid so each row, column, and 3×3 box contains digits 1-9 exactly once. This is constraint satisfaction via backtracking: find the next empty cell, try digits 1-9, check validity, recurse, and backtrack if stuck.

**Optimization:** Track which digits are used per row, column, and box using boolean arrays for O(1) checks instead of O(9) scans.

```python
# Python — Sudoku Solver
def solve_sudoku(board):
    rows = [set() for _ in range(9)]
    cols = [set() for _ in range(9)]
    boxes = [set() for _ in range(9)]

    # Pre-populate constraints from given clues
    for r in range(9):
        for c in range(9):
            if board[r][c] != '.':
                d = board[r][c]
                rows[r].add(d)
                cols[c].add(d)
                boxes[(r // 3) * 3 + c // 3].add(d)

    def is_valid(r, c, d):
        box_id = (r // 3) * 3 + c // 3
        return d not in rows[r] and d not in cols[c] and d not in boxes[box_id]

    def backtrack():
        for r in range(9):
            for c in range(9):
                if board[r][c] != '.':
                    continue
                box_id = (r // 3) * 3 + c // 3
                for d in '123456789':
                    if not is_valid(r, c, d):
                        continue
                    board[r][c] = d
                    rows[r].add(d)
                    cols[c].add(d)
                    boxes[box_id].add(d)
                    if backtrack():
                        return True
                    # backtrack
                    board[r][c] = '.'
                    rows[r].remove(d)
                    cols[c].remove(d)
                    boxes[box_id].remove(d)
                return False  # no digit worked for this cell
        return True  # no empty cell found — solved!

    backtrack()
    return board
```

```java
// Java — Sudoku Solver
public class SudokuSolver {
    public void solveSudoku(char[][] board) {
        boolean[][] rows = new boolean[9][10];
        boolean[][] cols = new boolean[9][10];
        boolean[][] boxes = new boolean[9][10];

        for (int r = 0; r < 9; r++)
            for (int c = 0; c < 9; c++)
                if (board[r][c] != '.') {
                    int d = board[r][c] - '0';
                    rows[r][d] = cols[c][d] = boxes[boxId(r,c)][d] = true;
                }
        backtrack(board, rows, cols, boxes);
    }

    private boolean backtrack(char[][] board, boolean[][] rows,
                              boolean[][] cols, boolean[][] boxes) {
        for (int r = 0; r < 9; r++)
            for (int c = 0; c < 9; c++) {
                if (board[r][c] != '.') continue;
                int box = boxId(r, c);
                for (int d = 1; d <= 9; d++) {
                    if (rows[r][d] || cols[c][d] || boxes[box][d]) continue;
                    board[r][c] = (char)('0' + d);
                    rows[r][d] = cols[c][d] = boxes[box][d] = true;
                    if (backtrack(board, rows, cols, boxes)) return true;
                    board[r][c] = '.';
                    rows[r][d] = cols[c][d] = boxes[box][d] = false;
                }
                return false;
            }
        return true;
    }

    private int boxId(int r, int c) { return (r / 3) * 3 + c / 3; }
}
```

**Complexity:** Worst case O(9^(81)) but constraint propagation prunes this dramatically in practice. For valid puzzles, solving is nearly instantaneous.

**Interview Tip:** The box index formula `(r/3)*3 + (c/3)` maps any cell to one of nine 3×3 boxes. Memorize this — it appears in many Sudoku/grid problems. Interviewers may also ask about constraint propagation (AC-3 algorithm) as an optimization; mention it shows depth of knowledge.

